[SPEAKER_00] God is no longer bound by necessity to the son whose generation is a volitional act.

177
00:20:25,359 --> 00:20:27,460
[SPEAKER_00] Alexander is less explicit.

178
00:20:28,359 --> 00:20:32,599
[SPEAKER_00] Aksandric sources do not confirm the act of will,

179
00:20:32,599 --> 00:20:37,059
[SPEAKER_00] though Hanson argues that Syrian fragments suggest a similar position.

180
00:20:37,059 --> 00:20:42,960
[SPEAKER_00] For Alexander's son differs from the father as a ray differs from light.

181
00:20:42,960 --> 00:20:46,119
[SPEAKER_00] The father is the cause of the son,

182
00:20:46,119 --> 00:20:48,420
[SPEAKER_00] the cause of his hypostasis,

183
00:20:48,420 --> 00:20:50,559
[SPEAKER_00] begotten by the father's will.

184
00:20:50,559 --> 00:20:53,539
[SPEAKER_00] This position of Alexander is better interpreted

185
00:20:53,539 --> 00:20:57,099
[SPEAKER_00] as grounded in the Alexandrian tradition,

186
00:20:57,099 --> 00:20:59,980
[SPEAKER_00] specifically in origin,

187
00:20:59,980 --> 00:21:04,319
[SPEAKER_00] rather than as an agreement with Aries' teaching.

188
00:21:04,319 --> 00:21:08,339
[SPEAKER_00] In his circular letter to the Alexandrian church,

189
00:21:08,339 --> 00:21:12,039
[SPEAKER_00] Alexander opposes Aries' claim that the son,

190
00:21:12,039 --> 00:21:13,259
[SPEAKER_00] quote,

191
00:21:13,259 --> 00:21:16,019
[SPEAKER_00] that the son is not like the father essence,

192
00:21:16,019 --> 00:21:18,619
[SPEAKER_00] nor the true logos of God,

193
00:21:18,819 --> 00:21:26,720
[SPEAKER_00] accusing Aries of denying that the son is true to idio, logos, and wisdom of God.

194
00:21:26,720 --> 00:21:28,240
[SPEAKER_00] The term idios,

195
00:21:28,240 --> 00:21:30,619
[SPEAKER_00] later used by Athanasius,

196
00:21:30,619 --> 00:21:34,400
[SPEAKER_00] describes the relationship between the father and the son's essence.

197
00:21:35,059 --> 00:21:40,400
[SPEAKER_00] If Alexander accepts the son's generation as an act of father's will,

198
00:21:40,400 --> 00:21:45,740
[SPEAKER_00] for him it expressed the constancy of divine nature,

199
00:21:45,740 --> 00:21:48,380
[SPEAKER_00] not arbitrary volition.

200
00:21:48,380 --> 00:21:52,740
[SPEAKER_00] Alexander's role in the early Arian controversies were decisive,

201
00:21:52,740 --> 00:21:58,500
[SPEAKER_00] both in identifying doctrinally and acceptable elements of Aries' teaching,

202
00:21:59,140 --> 00:22:01,599
[SPEAKER_00] and in refuting them.

203
00:22:01,599 --> 00:22:07,200
[SPEAKER_00] His arguments later serve as a foundation for the reg hairs of orthodox theology,

204
00:22:07,200 --> 00:22:08,599
[SPEAKER_00] such as Athanasius,

205
00:22:08,599 --> 00:22:12,019
[SPEAKER_00] and indirectly for Capedotian fathers.

206
00:22:12,019 --> 00:22:15,839
[SPEAKER_00] While Aries considered the son's generation

207
00:22:15,839 --> 00:22:20,240
[SPEAKER_00] an act of the father's will,

208
00:22:20,240 --> 00:22:23,460
[SPEAKER_00] entailing both logical and temporal precedence,

209
00:22:25,059 --> 00:22:27,480
[SPEAKER_00] Alexander avoids this trap,

210
00:22:27,480 --> 00:22:31,539
[SPEAKER_00] asserting that the son is co-internal with the father

211
00:22:31,539 --> 00:22:33,359
[SPEAKER_00] and begotten without beginning.

212
00:22:33,359 --> 00:22:41,599
[SPEAKER_00] He emphasizes that any period posited by Aries

213
00:22:41,599 --> 00:22:45,400
[SPEAKER_00] before the son's generation can only be temporal

214
00:22:45,400 --> 00:22:48,880
[SPEAKER_00] and must not compromise the son's divinity,

215
00:22:49,460 --> 00:22:56,539
[SPEAKER_00] making clear that the logical precedence does not entail temporal precedence.

216
00:22:56,539 --> 00:22:58,220
[SPEAKER_00] In conclusion,

217
00:22:58,220 --> 00:23:02,700
[SPEAKER_00] the correspondence between Aries and Alexander for Alexander reveals

218
00:23:02,700 --> 00:23:05,160
[SPEAKER_00] how debates about the time and the wind

219
00:23:05,160 --> 00:23:08,299
[SPEAKER_00] being shaped by Nicene Creed.

220
00:23:08,299 --> 00:23:11,500
[SPEAKER_00] Aries claimed that there was a,

221
00:23:11,500 --> 00:23:13,319
[SPEAKER_00] when the son was not,

222
00:23:13,319 --> 00:23:15,400
[SPEAKER_00] so to preserve divine freedom,

223
00:23:15,519 --> 00:23:21,819
[SPEAKER_00] but subordinated the son compromising his divinity.

224
00:23:21,819 --> 00:23:24,460
[SPEAKER_00] Alexander countered this

225
00:23:24,460 --> 00:23:27,759
[SPEAKER_00] by distinguishing the father's unbegotteness as unique

226
00:23:27,759 --> 00:23:32,980
[SPEAKER_00] while affirming the son's co-eternity and begotteness without beginning.

227
00:23:32,980 --> 00:23:36,240
[SPEAKER_00] Drawing an Alexandrian tradition,

228
00:23:36,240 --> 00:23:39,819
[SPEAKER_00] methodist critic of origin and scription,

229
00:23:39,819 --> 00:23:42,519
[SPEAKER_00] Alexander provided a robust theological framework

230
00:23:42,519 --> 00:23:46,420
[SPEAKER_00] that safeguarded the father-son relationship.

231
00:23:46,420 --> 00:23:50,539
[SPEAKER_00] His arguments were instrumental in shaping the Nicene Creed,

232
00:23:50,539 --> 00:23:54,720
[SPEAKER_00] establishing the foundation for Trinitarian theology,

233
00:23:54,720 --> 00:23:58,920
[SPEAKER_00] and guiding subsequent patristic reflection

234
00:23:58,920 --> 00:24:02,799
[SPEAKER_00] on the unity and distinction within the Godhead.

235
00:24:02,799 --> 00:24:04,559
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you very much for your attention.

236
00:24:04,559 --> 00:24:04,660
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you.

